title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:strong>Uniqueness:</fr:strong> Suppose there are two complex numbers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[zv=1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[zw=1]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v=1v=(zw)v=(wz)v=w(zv)=w1=w]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Existence:</fr:strong> Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex>. We see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{2}+y^{2}>0]]></fr:tex> is nonzero, so the complex number
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[w=\frac {x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+\mathrm {i}\frac {-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}]]></fr:tex>
is well-defined. We just need to check <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[zw=1]]></fr:tex>, but the trick is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x+\mathrm {i} y)(x-\mathrm {i} y)=x^{2}+y^{2}]]></fr:tex> and the result follows immediately.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
